headline: President Trump unloads on Democrats over impeachment inquiry
subHeadline: Trump rails against Democrats and tells Republicans to get tougher; reaction and analysis on 'The Five.'

utterances.speaker: GREG GUTFELD, CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: Hi, I'm Greg Gutfeld with Dagen McDowell, Juan Williams, Jesse Watters, and she once mountain climbed a speed bump, Dana Perino -- "The Five." Tulsi and Hillary. Hillary and Tulsi. It's still on, and Tulsi's winning.

utterances.speaker: REP TULSI GABBARD (D-HI)
utterances.sentences: People warned me in 2016 that my endorsement of Bernie Sanders would be the end of my, quote, unquote, political career.  If they can falsely portray me as a traitor, then they can do it to anyone. If you stand up against Hillary, they will destroy you and discredit your message. But here's the truth, they will not intimidate us.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: It's like a message from the future. She's like a Hawaiian Sarah Connor. Even Trump weighed in. Ah, Hillary Clinton, if you've heard of her.

utterances.speaker: DONALD TRUMP, PRESIDENT OF THE UNITED STATES OF AMERICA
utterances.sentences: Hillary Clinton, if you've heard of her. She's someone that's accusing everybody of being a Russian agent. Anybody that is opposed of her is a Russian agent. Tulsi, I don't know Tulsi, but she's not a Russian agent. I don't know Jill Stein. I know she likes environment. I don't think she likes Russians. These people are sick. They're something wrong with them. But I think that Tulsi Gabbard probably got helped quite a bit by this stir.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Meanwhile, an MSNBC panel mocked Tulsi for not denying that she was a Russian asset.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.sentences: One thing that was interesting about Tulsi Gabbard's response, I mean, she went after Hillary Clinton, she was strong. She said that she wasn't going to run as a third party candidate. She never denied being a Russian asset.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.sentences: That was missing from her response, which you think that would be (INAUDIBLE) in the first line or two. It was not there.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: What a moronic giggle fest. Sorry, Tulsi's not an asset, but what a set of asses. Speaking of, here's Joy.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.sentences: She hasn't denied it. She hasn't said anything in her tweets. How dare you. It's outrageous. Of course, I'm not. She didn't say that. She's just going after Hillary. I just think that she could be a useful idiot the way Trump is a useful idiot to the Russians, that they see something. They say, oh, look, a useful idiot. Let's play this.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Joy calling someone an idiot. I say that's the pot calling the kettle black, but pots have a higher IQ. But this feud draws quite the contrast, if there's anyone who reminds you of the past, one of murky sleaze, it's a Clinton. Their favorite smear, Russian assets. They've said Trump was one. And now, they're saying it's a young clear-eyed female veteran who served her country while rejecting conventional ideology.  There's lots to disagree with on Tulsi, but at least you know she's real, which is why the Dems fear her. The party of identity politics can't figure her identity out.   Maybe that's why so many Republicans like her. She's isn't manufactured to please the bots at MSNBC, but Hillary is. Her bitter idiotic commentary keeps reminding you of why Trump won. Think about it. She says this so- called Russian asset would split the Democratic vote if she went rogue? No. She'll likely pull more R's than D's. Despite what Hillary claims, Tulsi is no Jill Stein. She's sane of that with a libertarian bent, one that's not to the left of the Dems, but to the right of the Dems. So not only is Hillary stupidly wrong about Tulsi, she makes it clear who the Republican asset really is. It's Hillary. Everytime she opens her mouth she makes the Dems looks sad. Are we sure she's not on Trump's payroll?  Dagen, I have a theory. I haven't named it yet, but I call it smear by external preference. That means you can be in a punk band, right? A very popular punk band, but among your fans are skinheads. So someone could say, oh, you're a skinhead band, or you're a skinhead asset. So she could have a ton of fans, some of them are Russian. Some of them are Canadian.  She can't help, likewise, we can't help who our fans are. So, if Canadians like you, are you a Canadian asset? Do you see my point?

utterances.speaker: DAGEN MCDOWELL, CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: Yes, I'm not a Canadian asset. I generally rebuff Justin Bieber and Jim Carrey at any opportunity. But you've mentioned the word bitter, and I wrote down, bitterness is Hillary's favorite color of lipstick. That's pretty clear. All of her failings, all of her failures, she can't take ownership of them. To her fans, and there're still a few, she should have been able to beat Trump as easy as driving through a McDonald's drive-thru, but she can't.   And in that puff podcast that she did, of course, she has to go after Fox News. But she longs for the day where there were just three television networks and a few newspapers, and she actually had the audacity to say it was a much more controllable environment. She said, so it's a lot harder for Americans to know what they're supposed to believe. That's how she views the world that she's out there to -- the American people know what they believe in, and they don't believe in you. Bye.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yeah. Dana, don't you agree that if Tulsi ran it would -- wouldn't it hurt Trump more than it would hurt the Dems? Because you hear it from Republicans, but independents more about how much they like Tulsi that anybody in the Dems, am I wrong? I sense that --

utterances.speaker: DANA PERINO, CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: I think that on the left, one of the things that they -- some on the left have a problem with Tulsi Gabbard because she would -- she's not anti-war, right? She's kind of a hawk, but she would use drones and things like that. And there are a lot of liberals who don't want that at all either.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Right.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Libertarians, I'm not sure, so much for that as well. But if you're a -- so 1.4 million people voted for Jill Stein in the election -- out of 330-odd-million people, that's not that many. But if you were one of them, would you be motivated to return to the Democratic poll after this, after Hillary going after Tulsi Gabbard, probably not. I don't necessarily mean -- I don't think that means that they're -- she's gonna -- all of a sudden turn into Republican voters. But Tulsi Gabbard also gain 50 thousand followers out for this. She got a ton of free publicity, and for what? Like, what has it accomplished for Hillary Clinton? I don't know if it's anything.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yeah, maybe more book sales, because she needs the money, you know. She need a forth house, Jesse. One of my smartest friends, Walter, is 100 percent positive that she's entering the race. One of my other smarter friends, Scott, says there's no way.

utterances.speaker: JESSE WATTERS, CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: Scott Adams?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes. Where would you say? Do you think this is all because she's coming back?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: No, I don't think she's going to enter the race. There's -- people don't like her. People don't like her on the right, they don't like her in the middle, and now a lot of people on the left don't like her.  She's a feminist, Greg. And she's smeared a female combat veteran.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: That's true.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Just think about that. This woman went to overseas to lay her life down for her country and Hillary is smearing her as a Russian. She probably actually had sniper fire over her head, whereas Hillary just lied about it. And then, Hillary is so tough on Russia? I mean, a few years ago, she was giggling with the reset button, laughing it up, yucking it up, she's so tough? A couple of years ago, she called Assad a reformer. A reformer.  And then -- I think it was in 2011, Nancy Pelosi whacks -- and a bunch of Democrats went over to Syria.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: John Kerry had dinner.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Shook hands with Assad. They didn't want -- now they have to kill him to be tough? And if you don't want to kill him, you're a Russian asset? It's so crazy now. The Democrats have never been tough on Russia.  Remember, I mean, they were like, you know, communist sympathizers 75 years ago. They were against everything Ronald Reagan was doing to defeat the Soviet Union. And, you know, Romney got mocked for saying Russia was a vet -- now, they turn around and they say, oh, if you're not against Russia, you know, they did all these kinds of things, pointed missiles at us. Proxy wars, but they hack a Democrat's computer, and all of the sudden we're in World War III? It's crazy. You cannot have a legitimate disagreement on the left over foreign policy now without getting smeared as a Russian agent.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: All right, Juan. Is she a Russian agent?

utterances.speaker: JUAN WILLIAMS, CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: I don't know.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Oh, Juan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: But I will say this --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Are you a Russian agent, Juan?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Could be. You know what I think -- you know, if you look just at the hard politics of it, Hillary Clinton has no political future. She's not running. And --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: And I think that what you have here is that she's free to speak her mind, and she does not want a repeat of what happened with a third- party candidate in 2016. Because remember, Jill Stein got 1 percent in Michigan, Wisconsin, Pennsylvania, that exceeded the margin of Trump's victory over Hillary Clinton. We're talking a big jump in terms of electoral votes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: But Tulsi isn't Jill.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Let me finish. It doesn't -- let me just say, and remember, Jill Stein -- Jill Stein had a dinner with Putin and Michael Flynn in 2015.  Where do you see? She gets like 2 percent right now in the polls. But guess what? She's all over R.T. She's all over Sputnik, right? She gets lots of attention. And I think this is what you're referring to, gets lots of attention from far right conspiracy people. They love her. The bots love her. You can understand why people are saying, hey, wait a second, are the Russians trying to exploit Tulsi Gabbard? She doesn't need to be a Russian asset. She can just be someone who's exploited to diminish Democratic --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: That goes to my point, which is -- you can't control an external preference. If someone is a fan of your band, you can't say no.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: No, but this is politics. And when politics -- if you see right-wing people supporting Tulsi Gabbard, they have a reason.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: No, actually, right-wing people supporting Tulsi Gabbard hurts them, because they won't vote for Trump.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: No, she's still being used by the right --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Juan, I think you're overplaying the bots. You guys control the whole media.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: We call you Mark Zuckerberg.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Oh, my gosh.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: President Trump hammers the Democrats over impeachment and what he wants Republicans to do. That's next.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: The impeachment fight heating up again as Democrats continues to rail against President Trump. The Republicans, they're laser focus on Adam Schiff, pushing to censor the intelligence committee chair over his handling of impeachment. Meanwhile, the president is fired up. Look at him at his cabinet meeting, going off on House Democrats who are pushing the inquiry, even calling out Republicans. As I say, take a look.

utterances.speaker: DONALD TRUMP, PRESIDENT OF THE UNITED STATES OF AMERICA
utterances.sentences: Well, I think the Democrats fight dirty. I think the Democrats are lousy politicians with lousy policies. But two things they have, they're vicious and they stick together. They don't have Mitt Romney in their midst. They don't have people like that that. And the Republicans have to get tougher and fight. We have some that are great fighters, but they have to get tougher and fight because the Democrats are trying to hurt the Republican Party for the election.  Pelosi, shifty Schiff, Schumer, these people are trying to destroy the country. It's a very bad thing what they're doing. The President of the United States should be allowed to run the country, not have to focus on this kind of crap.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Jesse, I would think that he's not trying to make sure that he's got his troops line up, you know, his impeachment approaches. But he had a tough week last week. I mean, we can go over Doral in which he had to reverse over the weekend that he was going to have the G7 there. He had the problem with Syria, and a lot of Republicans very critical position in the House vote.  And then, we had Nick Mulvaney, the chief of staff, who had -- I mean, you know, he was on Chris Wallace yesterday, and Chris just runs the tape and there he is saying there's a quid pro quo. So, is he now trying to get the Republicans to say, hey, enough, enough, we're just going to back our president.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Well, he's had tougher weeks. I mean, I've been on this show the whole presidency and there's been some tough weeks. And what happens after these tough weeks? He usually bounces back and he bounces back very strong. Of course, he's gonna have the Republicans get in line, and they will because it's partisan. The Democrat wants to impeach, but they want to do it in the dark. Republicans aren't going to stand for it. But, to be honest with you, going after Schiff is a legitimate thing. I mean, the guy wants to run for senate when Feinstein retires. That's his move. He fabricated quotes on national television. He worked with the whistle blower beforehand. The guy is totally corrupt. No one trusts him, OK? And I think he's leading the Democrats over a cliff and Nancy is allowing it to happen, because if you look around the country -- you know, we had Watergate, even Iran-contra, or Lewinsky, this scandal was consuming the nation. It's all you heard about. It's all everybody was talking about, because I remember Watergate.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: If you go out to Ohio, Florida -- just go out to the suburbs, leave Washington, leave Manhattan, talk to people, no one is talking about Ukraine. They're talking about football. They're talking about playoff baseball. They're talking about Jack Lemmon making money. No one is talking about this. And Trump has the advantage, he'll say the do-nothing Democrats are letting infrastructure and drug prices just sit there, collecting dust, and they're trying to impeach me in the dark, and we're raising a ton of money and you guys are dead broke over at the DNC.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Dana, the Wall Street Journal, New York Times, Washington Post, all this morning said the reason the president reversed himself on Doral was because of Republicans who made it clear --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Yeah, that was reported on Saturday. And, look, I think that if you're going to reverse anything that would be an easy one. That was announced on a Thursday, reversed by Sunday. To me, like no one -- that's like in the blink of the eye, that's not even a comma in the history books, and they'll move on. I think that the Republicans are focused on process to defend the president because that's their best argument right now. And I don't think it's so much Schiff, himself, because his name I.D. isn't high enough, but it's the -- that the whole process seems to be geared to hurt the president, and that it's all being done in secret.  People in that right now -- everything is out in the open about everything, all the time, we're all over-sharing, and this is the one thing that can't be done in public. Like, you hear about these witnesses going behind closed doors. You maybe hear a little bit about the testimony, but you don't see transcripts. You don't actually see the people. I think that their process point to the extent that they have a good one right now is that I do think the president will continue to be very frustrated. He will never think that the Republicans do enough to defend him, but he does a really good job of defending himself.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: What do you think of the nicknames, shifty Schiff, the crazy Nancy --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Schiff is a perfect target because he seems -- I mean, a deer in the headlights looks at him and says, that's a deer in the headlights. He's like -- he's so stiff he could model caskets. And then you got -- he is right about Mitt. Mitt got targeted. He's like the weakest gazelle in the Serengeti. You know, they know that he's got a lot of baggage, so they can slow him down and use him against him. But I'm not going to fault the Democrats on this because when you're out of power, this is what you do. It's like, Reagan was demonized, Bush was demonized, Clinton was demonized, Bush was demonized, Obama was demonized, now Trump. The engine of demonization begins with being out of power. You've got to keep busy. Why help these guys? You're hoping to get them out of the White House. But what's new, I think, is that for every large effort unleashed by the Democrats, there's an equally large response. The ideal old world was -- it was a one-way street. You could just hammer away at Reagan. You could hammer away at Bush. And, you know, they called Bush a warmonger. And Bush has said, you know, you can't do that. It's now a two-lane blacktop and the traffic is coming back harsh because -- and that's why I think it's so intense because Trump isn't gonna take it. And it's no --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: And also he has technology --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: -- that others didn't have.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: That is true. That is true.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: So, Dagen, let's go to the point that Dana was making that she says the process argument is the president's best argument at this point his defense. Of course, the Democrats say that the constitution says the House of Representative, an equal branch of government, and they have total control over impeachment when and how it's done.

utterances.speaker: MCDOWELL
utterances.sentences: They have total control, it's up in the air, but the way they're going about it is wrong for this reason, because it's in secret, nobody is seeing anything. All you see, to your point, is the messenger. Who's your messenger? Schiff? He can't even read a parody, and the American people know it's a parody. He's such a bad actor. And then, Nancy Pelosi, all she's got -- her office has to put out a four-page fact sheet? She's got a photo of her stick in her finger toward the president? She looks like a scold second grade teacher who might thump you on the head, worst-case scenario. But Trump, he is bombastic, he's a bloviator, but he is the best marketing machine the Republicans have ever seen and may be politics.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: All right. Bernie Sanders picking up a big endorsement over the weekend from Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez. We've got that and much, much more right here on THE FIVE, and the 2020 roundup, next.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Welcome back. Let's get to our 2020 round up, Elizabeth Warren taken a lot of heat for 2020 rivals for not explaining how she will pay for her Medicare for all plan, and whether taxes on the middle class will go up. The candidate now says she's going to tell us all very soon.

utterances.speaker: SEN. ELIZABETH WARREN (D-MA)
utterances.sentences: I plan over the next few weeks to put out a plan that talks about, specifically, the cost of Medicare for all and, specifically, how we pay for it.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: OK. So far, Jesse, she's been kind of Teflon on this cycle. She hasn't had to really take any sling and arrows, but this one might get her.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Well, it's a layup for Democrats on healthcare. All you have to say is, let's run on expanding Obamacare. How hard is that? How do I know that and they don't know that?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: You know what? That's a great point.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I mean, it's like so popular, Obama is popular. Just saying I'm going to strengthen it, I'm going to reinforce, I'm going to save it --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I bet Biden is barely doing that. He's getting crushed. She can't pay for that. If she had that idea in the boardroom, corporate America, she gets laughed out of there.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Biden, Klobucher, and Buttigieg, all in the debate last week, Juan, ganged up on her and said, you can't just say that you're gonna do Medicare for all, but not explain to us how are you going to pay for it.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I agree. And I do think that she's been taking some slings on this one. The thing is, what's interest me is that Bernie does not, you know, stick it in there. He doesn't knife her on this. Bernie's very circumspect when it comes to her. And I think, of course, that's because he recognizes that their base is very similar. It might be the same thing.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: You see that same ticket.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: But -- oh, you mean --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Sanders, Warren. Warren, Sanders.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I don't know about that, but it could be, maybe. But I will say this, I mean, you know, the thing about Jesse's point, it's well taken. I think that's why Biden is saying Obamacare just needs to be strengthen. Americans right now used to be Obamacare wasn't popular, now it's more than 55 percent. But I will say, Trump has no plan and she doesn't -- rather than saying, hey, the status quo is not good because prices, premiums, deductibles, keep going up. She's suffering a self-inflicted injury on this one.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Dagen, now that she's said she's going to do this in a few weeks. How much scrutiny is that going to get?

utterances.speaker: MCDOWELL
utterances.sentences: It is going to get more scrutiny because she's waited so long and, literally, dodged over a dozen times are taxes going to go up for the middle class? And it's astonishing that she would stand in Ohio, in front of union members and, essentially, tell them their private insurance is going away. What's the point of a union if not to negotiate your health care benefits, past, present, and future? That she would not be able to pay for this. She's already going to raise social security taxes, raise corporate profit taxes, a new wealth tax, and it's already allocated to other things, like paying for college tuition (INAUDIBLE). So, yeah, your taxes are going -- everybody's taxes going up.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Not enough to have a plan and not say how you're going to pay for it?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yeah, you know, liberal economics they're like birthday party magicians, it's only entertaining to the children if they don't see how it's done, because once you see them taking the money from mommy and daddy, no clothes, no iPhone, no Netflix, you're no longer a fan of the magician. Can I point out, I love how she can't detail her plans, but when it comes to historical fiction, she's like a regular Gorvadol, like, how do you pay for your health care? She's like, nothing. But if you ask her what it was like to be the first black lesbian on the moon, she'd say it was a privilege.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Bernie Sanders picking up a big endorsement from fellow socialist Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez. AOC heaping praise on the 2020 Democrat during a rally, Saturday. Watch.

utterances.speaker: REP. ALEXANDRIA OCASIO-CORTEZ (D-NY)
utterances.sentences: We, right now, have one of the best Democratic presidential primary field in a generation. And much of that is thanks to the work that Bernie Sanders has done in his entire life.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Juan, the Bernie Sanders campaign getting a little more life breathes into the campaign, and they didn't talked about heart attacks anymore.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Oh, Dana.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: What I'm saying that they didn't.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I think there was a slump after that. After he said he might not be on the campaign trail as much. But this brings into question, how much is an endorsement worth these days because she is the personification of a movement for a lot of young people on the left. But I don't know that it's actually going to mean a bump in his support, I don't think so. It's not - I think Obama, when he endorses, I think you could see it as passing the torch to the next. But I'm not sure that her endorsement is necessarily a game-changer.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: He endorsed Justin Trudeau before Biden. That's kind of sad. Can I just say that, now I'm glad that it's OK to support old white men? I think that she's broken the seal. But it is also brave that she did Bernie Sanders because everybody is stealing from him. She basically endorsed Jimmy Hendrix and not Lenny Kravitz.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: You mean not--

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Nor like Warren, yes, who is Lenny Kravitz?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I think that spells dooms for the Democrats in the general election, because Bernie is not going to be the nominee. It's going to be Warren, or it's going to be Biden. So, the Squad is going to be at odds with whoever the nominee is going to be. And they're going to have to patch it up in a real fake and phony way in order to show party unity and it's not really going to go over too well.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: I have one last thing, Mayor Pete, he's surging in Iowa. A new poll has him jumping seven points since June into third place, putting him within striking distance of Joe Biden and Liz Warren. If you look at that poll there, Dagen, part of that is organization. And so, does it show that he can actually run a campaign as a business manager?

utterances.speaker: MCDOWELL
utterances.sentences: Sort of. Though the fundraising has certainly helped him a lot in terms of his ad buy for - more than $4.5 million on digital ads alone in last quarter. A lot of TV ads in Iowa and in New Hampshire. But he's fourth place behind Kamala Harris and virtually every other state, South Carolina, Nevada and California. So, he's got a long way to go. His husband is extremely charming. He's got two cool dogs.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: He has a husband?

utterances.speaker: MCDOWELL
utterances.sentences: Buddy. And what's the other - Truman is the other dog's name. I see. I'm distracted because now I'm thinking about Lenny Kravitz and his pants splitting open.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Momentum, if you look good in Iowa, we're 105 days till that vote.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I must say that last comment caught me off-guard.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: That's - we'll tell you at the commercial break.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: But I think Buttigieg is going up. The thing is, he has no support from minorities. And I don't see how the Democratic nominee--

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Can he turn that around, Jesse?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I don't know. I don't think so. But he's gotten an opening because Biden has now kind of let him get in there because Biden doesn't talk about middle class issues anymore. And then Warren has given him an opening on health care, and he's kind of threading the needle.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Threading the needle. Very good cliche.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Thank you.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: All right. Coming up, President Trump targeted in a giant billboard ad, yet Democrats and the media mostly silent.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Liberals always hysterical over President Trump's tone and rhetoric. But they never seem to care about the many threats of violence against him. Here are just a few examples popping up. A clothing company bought a disturbing 30-foot tall billboard in Times Square depicting Trump being hogtied and stomped on. And Hollywood liberal Barbra Streisand tweeted out this cartoon of Nancy Pelosi impaling Trump with a giant high heel, ouch. She's kind of a hawk, but she would use drones and things like that. And there are a lot of liberals who don't want that at all either.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Libertarians, I'm not sure, so much for that as well. But if you're a -- so 1.4 million people voted for Jill Stein in the election -- out of 330-odd-million people, that's not that many. But if you were one of them, would you be motivated to return to the Democratic poll after this, after Hillary going after Tulsi Gabbard, probably not. I don't necessarily mean -- I don't think that means that they're -- she's gonna -- all of a sudden turn into Republican voters. But Tulsi Gabbard also gain 50 thousand followers out for this. She got a ton of free publicity, and for what? Like, what has it accomplished for Hillary Clinton? I don't know if it's anything.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah, maybe more book sales, because she needs the money, you know. She need a forth house, Jesse. One of my smartest friends, Walter, is 100 percent positive that she's entering the race. One of my other smarter friends, Scott, says there's no way.

utterances.speaker: JESSE WATTERS, CO-HOST
utterances.utterance: Scott Adams?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes. Where would you say? Do you think this is all because she's coming back?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: No, I don't think she's going to enter the race. There's -- people don't like her. People don't like her on the right, they don't like her in the middle, and now a lot of people on the left don't like her. She's a feminist, Greg. And she's smeared a female combat veteran.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: That's true.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Just think about that. This woman went to overseas to lay her life down for her country and Hillary is smearing her as a Russian. She probably actually had sniper fire over her head, whereas Hillary just lied about it. And then, Hillary is so tough on Russia? I mean, a few years ago, she was giggling with the reset button, laughing it up, yucking it up, she's so tough? A couple of years ago, she called Assad a reformer. A reformer. And then -- I think it was in 2011, Nancy Pelosi whacks -- and a bunch of Democrats went over to Syria.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: John Kerry had dinner.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Shook hands with Assad. They didn't want -- now they have to kill him to be tough? And if you don't want to kill him, you're a Russian asset? It's so crazy now. The Democrats have never been tough on Russia. Remember, I mean, they were like, you know, communist sympathizers 75 years ago. They were against everything Ronald Reagan was doing to defeat the Soviet Union. And, you know, Romney got mocked for saying Russia was a vet -- now, they turn around and they say, oh, if you're not against Russia, you know, they did all these kinds of things, pointed missiles at us. Proxy wars, but they hack a Democrat's computer, and all of the sudden we're in World War III? It's crazy. You cannot have a legitimate disagreement on the left over foreign policy now without getting smeared as a Russian agent.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: All right, Juan. Is she a Russian agent?

utterances.speaker: JUAN WILLIAMS, CO-HOST
utterances.utterance: I don't know.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Oh, Juan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: But I will say this --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Are you a Russian agent, Juan?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Could be. You know what I think -- you know, if you look just at the hard politics of it, Hillary Clinton has no political future. She's not running. And --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: And I think that what you have here is that she's free to speak her mind, and she does not want a repeat of what happened with a third- party candidate in 2016. Because remember, Jill Stein got 1 percent in Michigan, Wisconsin, Pennsylvania, that exceeded the margin of Trump's victory over Hillary Clinton. We're talking a big jump in terms of electoral votes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: But Tulsi isn't Jill.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Let me finish. It doesn't -- let me just say, and remember, Jill Stein -- Jill Stein had a dinner with Putin and Michael Flynn in 2015. Where do you see? She gets like 2 percent right now in the polls. But guess what? She's all over R.T. She's all over Sputnik, right? She gets lots of attention. And I think this is what you're referring to, gets lots of attention from far right conspiracy people. They love her. The bots love her. You can understand why people are saying, hey, wait a second, are the Russians trying to exploit Tulsi Gabbard? She doesn't need to be a Russian asset. She can just be someone who's exploited to diminish Democratic --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: That goes to my point, which is -- you can't control an external preference. If someone is a fan of your band, you can't say no.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: No, but this is politics. And when politics -- if you see right-wing people supporting Tulsi Gabbard, they have a reason.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: No, actually, right-wing people supporting Tulsi Gabbard hurts them, because they won't vote for Trump.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: No, she's still being used by the right --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Juan, I think you're overplaying the bots. You guys control the whole media.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: We call you Mark Zuckerberg.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Oh, my gosh.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: President Trump hammers the Democrats over impeachment and what he wants Republicans to do. That's next.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: The impeachment fight heating up again as Democrats continues to rail against President Trump. The Republicans, they're laser focus on Adam Schiff, pushing to censor the intelligence committee chair over his handling of impeachment. Meanwhile, the president is fired up. Look at him at his cabinet meeting, going off on House Democrats who are pushing the inquiry, even calling out Republicans. As I say, take a look.

utterances.speaker: DONALD TRUMP, PRESIDENT OF THE UNITED STATES OF AMERICA
utterances.utterance: Well, I think the Democrats fight dirty. I think the Democrats are lousy politicians with lousy policies. But two things they have, they're vicious and they stick together. They don't have Mitt Romney in their midst. They don't have people like that that. And the Republicans have to get tougher and fight. We have some that are great fighters, but they have to get tougher and fight because the Democrats are trying to hurt the Republican Party for the election. Pelosi, shifty Schiff, Schumer, these people are trying to destroy the country. It's a very bad thing what they're doing. The President of the United States should be allowed to run the country, not have to focus on this kind of crap.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Jesse, I would think that he's not trying to make sure that he's got his troops line up, you know, his impeachment approaches. But he had a tough week last week. I mean, we can go over Doral in which he had to reverse over the weekend that he was going to have the G7 there. He had the problem with Syria, and a lot of Republicans very critical position in the House vote. And then, we had Nick Mulvaney, the chief of staff, who had -- I mean, you know, he was on Chris Wallace yesterday, and Chris just runs the tape and there he is saying there's a quid pro quo. So, is he now trying to get the Republicans to say, hey, enough, enough, we're just going to back our president.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Well, he's had tougher weeks. I mean, I've been on this show the whole presidency and there's been some tough weeks. And what happens after these tough weeks? He usually bounces back and he bounces back very strong. Of course, he's gonna have the Republicans get in line, and they will because it's partisan. The Democrat wants to impeach, but they want to do it in the dark. Republicans aren't going to stand for it. But, to be honest with you, going after Schiff is a legitimate thing. I mean, the guy wants to run for senate when Feinstein retires. That's his move. He fabricated quotes on national television. He worked with the whistle blower beforehand. The guy is totally corrupt. No one trusts him, OK? And I think he's leading the Democrats over a cliff and Nancy is allowing it to happen, because if you look around the country -- you know, we had Watergate, even Iran-contra, or Lewinsky, this scandal was consuming the nation. It's all you heard about. It's all everybody was talking about, because I remember Watergate.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: If you go out to Ohio, Florida -- just go out to the suburbs, leave Washington, leave Manhattan, talk to people, no one is talking about Ukraine. They're talking about football. They're talking about playoff baseball. They're talking about Jack Lemmon making money. No one is talking about this. And Trump has the advantage, he'll say the do-nothing Democrats are letting infrastructure and drug prices just sit there, collecting dust, and they're trying to impeach me in the dark, and we're raising a ton of money and you guys are dead broke over at the DNC.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Dana, the Wall Street Journal, New York Times, Washington Post, all this morning said the reason the president reversed himself on Doral was because of Republicans who made it clear --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yeah, that was reported on Saturday. And, look, I think that if you're going to reverse anything that would be an easy one. That was announced on a Thursday, reversed by Sunday. To me, like no one -- that's like in the blink of the eye, that's not even a comma in the history books, and they'll move on. I think that the Republicans are focused on process to defend the president because that's their best argument right now. And I don't think it's so much Schiff, himself, because his name I.D. isn't high enough, but it's the -- that the whole process seems to be geared to hurt the president, and that it's all being done in secret. People in that right now -- everything is out in the open about everything, all the time, we're all over-sharing, and this is the one thing that can't be done in public. Like, you hear about these witnesses going behind closed doors. You maybe hear a little bit about the testimony, but you don't see transcripts. You don't actually see the people. I think that their process point to the extent that they have a good one right now is that I do think the president will continue to be very frustrated. He will never think that the Republicans do enough to defend him, but he does a really good job of defending himself.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: What do you think of the nicknames, shifty Schiff, the crazy Nancy --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Schiff is a perfect target because he seems -- I mean, a deer in the headlights looks at him and says, that's a deer in the headlights. He's like -- he's so stiff he could model caskets. And then you got -- he is right about Mitt. Mitt got targeted. He's like the weakest gazelle in the Serengeti. You know, they know that he's got a lot of baggage, so they can slow him down and use him against him. But I'm not going to fault the Democrats on this because when you're out of power, this is what you do. It's like, Reagan was demonized, Bush was demonized, Clinton was demonized, Bush was demonized, Obama was demonized, now Trump. The engine of demonization begins with being out of power. You've got to keep busy. Why help these guys? You're hoping to get them out of the White House. But what's new, I think, is that for every large effort unleashed by the Democrats, there's an equally large response. The ideal old world was -- it was a one-way street. You could just hammer away at Reagan. You could hammer away at Bush. And, you know, they called Bush a warmonger. And Bush has said, you know, you can't do that. It's now a two-lane blacktop and the traffic is coming back harsh because -- and that's why I think it's so intense because Trump isn't gonna take it. And it's no --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: And also he has technology --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: -- that others didn't have.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: That is true. That is true.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: So, Dagen, let's go to the point that Dana was making that she says the process argument is the president's best argument at this point his defense. Of course, the Democrats say that the constitution says the House of Representative, an equal branch of government, and they have total control over impeachment when and how it's done.

utterances.speaker: MCDOWELL
utterances.utterance: They have total control, it's up in the air, but the way they're going about it is wrong for this reason, because it's in secret, nobody is seeing anything. All you see, to your point, is the messenger. Who's your messenger? Schiff? He can't even read a parody, and the American people know it's a parody. He's such a bad actor. And then, Nancy Pelosi, all she's got -- her office has to put out a four-page fact sheet? She's got a photo of her stick in her finger toward the president? She looks like a scold second grade teacher who might thump you on the head, worst-case scenario. But Trump, he is bombastic, he's a bloviator, but he is the best marketing machine the Republicans have ever seen and may be politics.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: All right. Bernie Sanders picking up a big endorsement over the weekend from Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez. We've got that and much, much more right here on THE FIVE, and the 2020 roundup, next.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Welcome back. Let's get to our 2020 round up, Elizabeth Warren taken a lot of heat for 2020 rivals for not explaining how she will pay for her Medicare for all plan, and whether taxes on the middle class will go up. The candidate now says she's going to tell us all very soon.

utterances.speaker: SEN. ELIZABETH WARREN (D-MA)
utterances.utterance: I plan over the next few weeks to put out a plan that talks about, specifically, the cost of Medicare for all and, specifically, how we pay for it.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: OK. So far, Jesse, she's been kind of Teflon on this cycle. She hasn't had to really take any sling and arrows, but this one might get her.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Well, it's a layup for Democrats on healthcare. All you have to say is, let's run on expanding Obamacare. How hard is that? How do I know that and they don't know that?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: You know what? That's a great point.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I mean, it's like so popular, Obama is popular. Just saying I'm going to strengthen it, I'm going to reinforce, I'm going to save it --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I bet Biden is barely doing that. He's getting crushed. She can't pay for that. If she had that idea in the boardroom, corporate America, she gets laughed out of there.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Biden, Klobucher, and Buttigieg, all in the debate last week, Juan, ganged up on her and said, you can't just say that you're gonna do Medicare for all, but not explain to us how are you going to pay for it.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I agree. And I do think that she's been taking some slings on this one. The thing is, what's interest me is that Bernie does not, you know, stick it in there. He doesn't knife her on this. Bernie's very circumspect when it comes to her. And I think, of course, that's because he recognizes that their base is very similar. It might be the same thing.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: You see that same ticket.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: But -- oh, you mean --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Sanders, Warren. Warren, Sanders.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I don't know about that, but it could be, maybe. But I will say this, I mean, you know, the thing about Jesse's point, it's well taken. I think that's why Biden is saying Obamacare just needs to be strengthen. Americans right now used to be Obamacare wasn't popular, now it's more than 55 percent. But I will say, Trump has no plan and she doesn't -- rather than saying, hey, the status quo is not good because prices, premiums, deductibles, keep going up. She's suffering a self-inflicted injury on this one.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Dagen, now that she's said she's going to do this in a few weeks. How much scrutiny is that going to get?

utterances.speaker: MCDOWELL
utterances.utterance: It is going to get more scrutiny because she's waited so long and, literally, dodged over a dozen times are taxes going to go up for the middle class? And it's astonishing that she would stand in Ohio, in front of union members and, essentially, tell them their private insurance is going away. What's the point of a union if not to negotiate your health care benefits, past, present, and future? That she would not be able to pay for this. She's already going to raise social security taxes, raise corporate profit taxes, a new wealth tax, and it's already allocated to other things, like paying for college tuition (INAUDIBLE). So, yeah, your taxes are going -- everybody's taxes going up.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Not enough to have a plan and not say how you're going to pay for it?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah, you know, liberal economics they're like birthday party magicians, it's only entertaining to the children if they don't see how it's done, because once you see them taking the money from mommy and daddy, no clothes, no iPhone, no Netflix, you're no longer a fan of the magician. Can I point out, I love how she can't detail her plans, but when it comes to historical fiction, she's like a regular Gorvadol, like, how do you pay for your health care? She's like, nothing. But if you ask her what it was like to be the first black lesbian on the moon, she'd say it was a privilege.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Bernie Sanders picking up a big endorsement from fellow socialist Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez. AOC heaping praise on the 2020 Democrat during a rally, Saturday. Watch.

utterances.speaker: REP. ALEXANDRIA OCASIO-CORTEZ (D-NY)
utterances.utterance: We, right now, have one of the best Democratic presidential primary field in a generation. And much of that is thanks to the work that Bernie Sanders has done in his entire life.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Juan, the Bernie Sanders campaign getting a little more life breathes into the campaign, and they didn't talked about heart attacks anymore.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Oh, Dana.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: What I'm saying that they didn't.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I think there was a slump after that. After he said he might not be on the campaign trail as much. But this brings into question, how much is an endorsement worth these days because she is the personification of a movement for a lot of young people on the left. But I don't know that it's actually going to mean a bump in his support, I don't think so. It's not - I think Obama, when he endorses, I think you could see it as passing the torch to the next. But I'm not sure that her endorsement is necessarily a game-changer.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: He endorsed Justin Trudeau before Biden. That's kind of sad. Can I just say that, now I'm glad that it's OK to support old white men? I think that she's broken the seal. But it is also brave that she did Bernie Sanders because everybody is stealing from him. She basically endorsed Jimmy Hendrix and not Lenny Kravitz.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: You mean not--

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Nor like Warren, yes, who is Lenny Kravitz?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I think that spells dooms for the Democrats in the general election, because Bernie is not going to be the nominee. It's going to be Warren, or it's going to be Biden. So, the Squad is going to be at odds with whoever the nominee is going to be. And they're going to have to patch it up in a real fake and phony way in order to show party unity and it's not really going to go over too well.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I have one last thing, Mayor Pete, he's surging in Iowa. A new poll has him jumping seven points since June into third place, putting him within striking distance of Joe Biden and Liz Warren. If you look at that poll there, Dagen, part of that is organization. And so, does it show that he can actually run a campaign as a business manager?

utterances.speaker: MCDOWELL
utterances.utterance: Sort of. Though the fundraising has certainly helped him a lot in terms of his ad buy for - more than $4.5 million on digital ads alone in last quarter. A lot of TV ads in Iowa and in New Hampshire. But he's fourth place behind Kamala Harris and virtually every other state, South Carolina, Nevada and California. So, he's got a long way to go. His husband is extremely charming. He's got two cool dogs.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: He has a husband?

utterances.speaker: MCDOWELL
utterances.utterance: Buddy. And what's the other - Truman is the other dog's name. I see. I'm distracted because now I'm thinking about Lenny Kravitz and his pants splitting open.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Momentum, if you look good in Iowa, we're 105 days till that vote.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I must say that last comment caught me off-guard.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: That's - we'll tell you at the commercial break.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: But I think Buttigieg is going up. The thing is, he has no support from minorities. And I don't see how the Democratic nominee--

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Can he turn that around, Jesse?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I don't know. I don't think so. But he's gotten an opening because Biden has now kind of let him get in there because Biden doesn't talk about middle class issues anymore. And then Warren has given him an opening on health care, and he's kind of threading the needle.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Threading the needle. Very good cliche.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Thank you.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: All right. Coming up, President Trump targeted in a giant billboard ad, yet Democrats and the media mostly silent.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Liberals always hysterical over President Trump's tone and rhetoric. But they never seem to care about the many threats of violence against him. Here are just a few examples popping up. A clothing company bought a disturbing 30-foot tall billboard in Times Square depicting Trump being hogtied and stomped on. And Hollywood liberal Barbra Streisand tweeted out this cartoon of Nancy Pelosi impaling Trump with a giant high heel, ouch. And on top of all that, Beto O'Rourke is at it again, comparing President Trump to Nazis.

utterances.speaker: BETO O'ROURKE (D) PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE
utterances.utterance: President Trump, perhaps inspired by gerbils and the propagandists of the Third Reich seem to employ this tactic that the bigger the lie, the more obscene the injustice, the more dizzying the pace of this bizarre behavior, the less likely we are to be able to do something about it.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: All right, Juan, I'm not going to get so worked up over a billboard or a cartoon of a high heel. But what I will get worked up about is the hypocrisy. I mean, there is a guy like at a Tea Party rally with an Obama sign and like they thought there was going to be like an armed insurrection in the White House. But they have like major league threats against President Trump and no one seems to care on the Left.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Wait a minute, you mean the billboard was a threat or they brought--

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I mean just violent imagery, violent rhetoric. It just never goes the same way.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, it's violent imagery, I mean look, I think that the President's rhetoric I mean, - you know where I think of it. Let's just be fair, Jesse. If you want to condemn this, then I guess you have to condemn that video last week where they had the President shooting people in church who were his--

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes, we did.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: You know what, I didn't - I see that--

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Juan, you sit next to me.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: You said, oh, that was not the Trump campaign. It was in a small room at some--

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes, and I said they shouldn't have shown it.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: They shouldn't have made it, Jesse, that's the point.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: But you can't stop people from making stuff in their bedroom. That's crazy. And that's very leftist, by the way. The loudest, most aggressive anti-speech people are on the Left. ANTIFA is breaking up speeches. Academics are pursuing language bans. If you use a wrong pronoun, you could get disciplined or fired, I believe, in New York, according to the employment rules.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: In UK, you can get arrested.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes. Which is why, I'm totally for whatever anybody wants to do. What bothers me is watching Trump supporters getting spit on and getting hit by people because it's OK now to do that. And who makes it OK is obviously Beto. You compare Trump to Nazis, basically you're saying his supporters are Nazi sympathizers. You know, let's not forget the rodeo clown, remember the rodeo clown.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Oh, yes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Lost his job for wearing an Obama mask. Those were the good old days, right? This is I mean, look, you've got to be - I'm for do it whatever you want. I would rather have the speech and the billboards than the violence. And the violence is coming from the Left.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: No, it's not. Because, look--

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Have you seen these? You see what happened last couple weeks?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Who sent bombs to media organizations? That was a true--

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Who shot a bunch of people?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Oh, you mean like at the Pittsburgh synagogue? Oh, gee I wonder--

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: No, I'm talking about the Congressman--

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I'm just saying there has been a rise in hate crime in this country since Trump's been--

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes, and that was debunked.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: All right.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Read it out. I did it on the - it was debunked.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Juan refuses to condemn any violence that comes from the Left and just highlights Right-wing stuff.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: No, I just say let's be fair.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: It's true, Juan. You're not fair.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Let's be--

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: But you're not fair.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Let's equalize it.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: No, it's true. What do you think about Beto with a Nazi rhetoric?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: This is like the last gasp of his campaign.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes, he's going down.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: He's a zombie candidacy. He just doesn't know he's dead yet.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Wow, that hurts.
